<subSubSection pageId="4" pageNumber="135" type="distribution">
<paragraph blockId="4.[151,1436,1647,2032]" pageId="4" pageNumber="135">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,345,1719,1744]" pageId="4" pageNumber="135">Distribution</emphasis>
. The 
<typeStatus box="[417,465,1720,1744]" pageId="4" pageNumber="135">type</typeStatus>
material for this species was collected from hydrothermal vents in the East Scotia Ridge, Southern Ocean, at 
<quantity box="[462,620,1755,1780]" metricMagnitude="3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.4305" metricValueMax="1.462" metricValueMin="1.399" pageId="4" pageNumber="135" unit="m" value="1430.5" valueMax="1462.0" valueMin="1399.0">1399–1462 m</quantity>
depth. This locality is thousands of kilometers away from the location where this juvenile specimen was obtained.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection lastPageId="5" lastPageNumber="136" pageId="4" pageNumber="135" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="4.[151,1436,1647,2032]" pageId="4" pageNumber="135">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,308,1827,1852]" pageId="4" pageNumber="135">Remarks</emphasis>
. It is difficult to determine species identity of juvenile stages in this genus (as in general in pycnogonids), especially as most of the species descriptions lack the description of the juvenile. However, the characters of this specimen agreed mostly with those of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="? Arango &amp; Linse" authorityYear="2015" box="[813,938,1899,1923]" class="Pycnogonida" family="Ammotheidae" genus="Sericosura" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Pantopoda" pageId="4" pageNumber="135" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="bamberi">
<emphasis box="[813,938,1899,1923]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="135">S. bamberi</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. Apart from the weak chelae with smooth fingers and not fully developed ovigers, the juvenile is tentatively assigned to 
<taxonomicName authorityName="? Arango &amp; Linse" authorityYear="2015" box="[1069,1194,1935,1959]" class="Pycnogonida" family="Ammotheidae" genus="Sericosura" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Pantopoda" pageId="4" pageNumber="135" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="bamberi">
<emphasis box="[1069,1194,1935,1959]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="135">S. bamberi</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
based on the sevensegmented palps, bent bulky proboscis, funnel-shaped cephalon and an overall setose appearance (
<bibRefCitation pageId="4" pageNumber="135" refId="ref3234" refString="Arango, C. P. &amp; Linse, K. (2015) New Sericosura (Pycnogonida: Ammotheidae) from deep-sea hydrothermal vents in the Southern Ocean. Zootaxa, 3995 (1), 37 - 50. https: // doi. org / 10.11646 / zootaxa. 3995.1.5" type="journal article">Arango and Linse 2015</bibRefCitation>
) (
<figureCitation box="[301,370,2007,2032]" captionStart="FIGURE 2" captionStartId="3.[151,250,1388,1410]" captionTargetBox="[340,1247,193,1366]" captionTargetId="figure@3.[340,1247,193,1366]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="FIGURE 2. Sericosura duanqiaoensis sp. n., 34IV-TVG0802, male holotype: A, trunk, dorsal view; B, trunk, ventral view; C, leg 2; D, leg 3; E, F, palp, lateral view, arrow indicating the protuberance and tubercle." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/1247242/files/figure.png" pageId="4" pageNumber="135">Fig. 2</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="5.[151,1437,151,429]" pageId="5" pageNumber="136">
The morphological differences between the juvenile and the 
<typeStatus box="[892,940,152,176]" pageId="5" pageNumber="136">type</typeStatus>
specimen of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="? Arango &amp; Linse" authorityYear="2015" box="[1096,1218,152,176]" class="Pycnogonida" family="Ammotheidae" genus="Sericosura" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Pantopoda" pageId="5" pageNumber="136" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="bamberi">
<emphasis box="[1096,1218,152,176]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="136">S. bamberi</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
were the height of ocular tubercle and length ratio of palp articles (
<figureCitation box="[706,870,188,213]" captionStart="FIGURE 2" captionStartId="3.[151,250,1388,1410]" captionTargetBox="[340,1247,193,1366]" captionTargetId="figure@3.[340,1247,193,1366]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="FIGURE 2. Sericosura duanqiaoensis sp. n., 34IV-TVG0802, male holotype: A, trunk, dorsal view; B, trunk, ventral view; C, leg 2; D, leg 3; E, F, palp, lateral view, arrow indicating the protuberance and tubercle." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/1247242/files/figure.png" pageId="5" pageNumber="136">Fig. 2-C, E, F</figureCitation>
). The ocular tubercle was not visible from dorsal view, and is lower than that of the 
<typeStatus box="[537,585,224,248]" pageId="5" pageNumber="136">type</typeStatus>
specimen. The length ratio of seventh palp article and fifth is nearly 3/5.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="5" pageNumber="136" type="reference_group">
<paragraph blockId="5.[151,1437,151,429]" pageId="5" pageNumber="136">
<taxonomicName authority="Child &amp; Segonzac, 1996" authorityName="Child &amp; Segonzac" authorityYear="1996" box="[199,706,260,285]" class="Pycnogonida" family="Ammotheidae" genus="Sericosura" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Pantopoda" pageId="5" pageNumber="136" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="cyrtoma">
<emphasis box="[199,419,260,284]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="136">Sericosura cyrtoma</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation box="[427,706,260,285]" pageId="5" pageNumber="136" refId="ref3625" refString="Child, C. A. &amp; Segonzac, M. (1996) Sericosura heteroscela and S. cyrtoma, new species, and other Pycnogonida from Atlantic and Pacific hydrothermal vents, with notes on habitat and environment. Proceedings of the Biological Society of Washington, 109 (4), 664 - 676." type="journal article">Child &amp; Segonzac, 1996</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Arango &amp; Linse" authorityYear="2015" box="[717,854,260,284]" class="Pycnogonida" family="Ammotheidae" genus="Sericosura" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Pantopoda" pageId="5" pageNumber="136" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="dimorpha">
<emphasis box="[717,854,260,284]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="136">S. dimorpha</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName authority="Arango &amp; Linse, 2015" authorityName="Arango &amp; Linse" authorityYear="2015" box="[909,1261,260,285]" class="Pycnogonida" family="Ammotheidae" genus="Sericosura" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Pantopoda" pageId="5" pageNumber="136" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="curva">
<emphasis box="[909,1002,260,284]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="136">S. curva</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation box="[1009,1261,260,285]" pageId="5" pageNumber="136" refId="ref3234" refString="Arango, C. P. &amp; Linse, K. (2015) New Sericosura (Pycnogonida: Ammotheidae) from deep-sea hydrothermal vents in the Southern Ocean. Zootaxa, 3995 (1), 37 - 50. https: // doi. org / 10.11646 / zootaxa. 3995.1.5" type="journal article">Arango &amp; Linse, 2015</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
had seven palp articles with the fifth being the longers, but the juvenile was easily distinguished from these species by the bent bulky proboscis. 
<bibRefCitation box="[355,656,332,357]" pageId="5" pageNumber="136" refId="ref3234" refString="Arango, C. P. &amp; Linse, K. (2015) New Sericosura (Pycnogonida: Ammotheidae) from deep-sea hydrothermal vents in the Southern Ocean. Zootaxa, 3995 (1), 37 - 50. https: // doi. org / 10.11646 / zootaxa. 3995.1.5" type="journal article">Arango and Linse (2015)</bibRefCitation>
pointed the variable height of ocular tubercle among individuals examined, so the lower ocular tubercle and longer fifth palp article were not considered sufficient reasons to assign the juvenile to a new species.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
